 al Saud]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Jos\u00e9 Marti]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of St. Andrew]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Liberator]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Republic (Serbia)]]\n[[Category:Chinese male writers]]\n[[Category:Sent-down youths]]\n[[Category:Tsinghua University alumni]]\n[[Category:Vice Presidents of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China philosophers]]\n[[Category:Victims of the Cultural Revolution]]\n[[Category:Chinese expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Communist writers]]\n[[Category:Chinese Marxists]]\n", "name_user": "Ojotaranios", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHuman rights policy:Grammatical changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xi_Jinping"}
{"title_page": "Andhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian state bus operator}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Primary sources|1=article|date=March 2008}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Andhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation\n| logo                = Andhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation logo.png\n| industry            = [[Public transport bus service]]\n| type                = Public Sector Corporation under the Ministry of Transport of the State [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]]\n| products            = [[Bus transport]], courier and parcel service\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|1958|01|11}}\n| area_served         = [[Andhra Pradesh]]<br/>[[Chhattisgarh]]<br/>[[Karnataka]]<br/>[[Odisha]]<br/>[[Tamil Nadu]]<br/>[[Telangana]]<br/>[[Yanam]] ([[Puducherry]])\n| key_people          = {{Unbulleted list\n  | Perni Venkataramaiah {{Small|([[Ministry of Transport|Transport Minister]], [[Government of Andhra Pradesh|Govt. of Andhra Pradesh]])}}\n  | [[Surendra Babu|Nimmagadda Surendra Babu]] {{Small|([[Indian Police Service|I.P.S.]]) ([[Vice-Chairman]] and [[Managing director|MD]])}}\n  }}\n| revenue             = {{decrease}} {{INRConvert|67|m}}<ref name=\"news.outlookindia.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2019/dec/08/andhra-government-hikes-bus-fares-marginally-to-ease-loss-burden-on-apsrtc-2073170.html |title=Andhra government hikes bus fares marginally to ease loss burden on APSRTC |work=Newindianexpress.com |accessdate=2020-04-18 }}</ref>\n| homepage            = {{URL|https://www.apsrtc.ap.gov.in/}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Vijayawada|Vijayawada, Andhra Pradesh]]\n| hq_location_country = India\n}}\n\n'''Andhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation''' (abbreviated as '''APSRTC'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/ap-state-road-transport-corporation-merger-happening-sooner-than-expected/article27709442.ece|title=AP State Road Transport Corporation merger happening sooner than expected?|last=Varma|first=P. Sujatha|date=2019-06-10|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-06-10|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>) is the state-owned [[road transport]] corporation in the [[States and union territories of India|Indian state]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. Its headquarters is located at NTR Administrative Block of RTC House in [[Pandit Nehru bus station]] of [[Vijayawada]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Naidu to open RTC block today|url=http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Andhra-Pradesh/2016-06-06/Naidu-to-open-RTC-block-today-/233065|accessdate=18 April 2017|work=The Hans India|language=en}}</ref> Many other Indian metro towns in [[Telangana]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Karnataka]], [[Odisha]], [[Yanam]] and [[Chhattisgarh]] are also linked with the APSRTC services.\n\nAPSRTC was the first state transport system which uses Live tracking facilities for tracking of busses. GPS (Global positioning system) is fixed in all types of busses.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correspondent|first=Our Special|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/naidu-launches-bus-tracking-system/article27560344.ece|title=Naidu launches bus-tracking system|date=2004-02-06|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAPSRTC was formed on 11 January 1958 as per ''Road Transport Corporations Act 1950''. Earlier, it was a part of [[Nizam State Railways - Road Transport Division|Nizam State Rail and Road Transport Department]].<ref name=\"apsrtc\">{{cite web|title=Profile |url=http://www.apsrtc.gov.in/profile.aspx |website=Andhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation |access-date=18 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315015215/http://apsrtc.gov.in/profile.aspx |archivedate=15 March 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\nConsequent upon [[Telangana movement|bifurcation of Andhra Pradesh state]] into Telangana and residual Andhra Pradesh, [[TSRTC]] is operated as a separate entity from 3 June 2015.[[APSRTC]] is working from Vijayawada (Pandit Nehru Bus Stand) as Headquarters for the state of  Andhra Pradesh.\n\n== Administration ==\nThe organisation is divided into four zones with twelve Regional Managers. It has a total of 11,678 buses (government-owned 8964; hire on rental 2714)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apsrtc.gov.in/profile.aspx|title=APSRTC - Profile|website=apsrtc.gov.in|access-date=2018-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930050308/http://www.apsrtc.gov.in/profile.aspx|archive-date=30 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> operating in {{Nowrap|44.15 lakh}} kilometers and has a total of 426 bus stations and 126 bus depots.<ref name=\"apsrtc\" /> From 30 January 2019, all the APSRTC vehicles in the state are registered as [[List of RTO districts in India|AP\u201339]], followed by \"Z\" and four digits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/vijayawada/2019/jan/31/new-ap-39-code-to-register-vehicles-in-state-launched-1932417.html|title=New \u2018AP 39\u2019 code to register vehicles in Andhra Pradesh launched|date=31 January 2019|work=The New Indian Express|accessdate=9 June 2019|location=Vijayawada}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\n[[File:Sattupalle - Eluru APS RTC bus on Polavaram canal.jpg|thumb|An APSRTC bus Enroute to [[Eluru]]]]\nAPSRTC operates various services, such as Vennela, Night Rider,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/visakhapatnam/apsrtc-adds-2-night-rider-buses-to-fleet/articleshow/68568807.cms|title=APSRTC adds 2 Night Rider buses to fleet|last=V|first=Kamalakara Rao|date=26 March 2019|website=The Times of India|location=Visakhapatnam|language=en|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref> Amaravati, Garuda Plus, Indra, Super Luxury, Ultra Deluxe / Deluxe, Express, Saptagiri Luxury, Saptagiri Express, Metro Express, Metro Luxury, Metro Luxury Semi Low Floor, Metro Deluxe, Telugu Velugu, City Ordinary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apsrtc.gov.in/Types%20Of%20Coaches.aspx|title=Types of Coaches of A.P.S.R.T.C.|website=A.P.S.R.T.C.|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Performance and earnings ==\n{{As of|February 2016}}, the organisation has a gross earnings of {{INRconvert|30.50|abbr=on}} per km., with a loss of {{INRconvert|-465000.8|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"apsrtc\" />\n\n== Awards and achievements ==\n* It entered the ''[[Guinness Book of World Records]]'' on 31 October 1999, with 22,000 buses making it the largest bus fleet in the world.<ref>{{cite news|title=RTC heads for split amid fears, anxiety|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/rtc-heads-for-split-amid-fears-anxiety/article6651459.ece|accessdate=18 March 2015|work=The Hindu|date=1 December 2014|location=Vijayawada}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Largest Fleet of Buses|url=http://www.worldrecordholdersclub.com/?p=592|work=worldrecordholdersclub|date=1 December 2012}}</ref>\n* Highest [[KMPL]] fuel efficiency for 2011-12 \u2013 Mofussil services and Vijayawada (urban division)<ref name=awards>{{cite web|title=APSRTC awards and achievements |url=http://www.apsrtc.gov.in/Achievements.pdf |publisher=Andhra_Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation |accessdate=18 March 2015 |format=PDF |date=7 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221115509/http://www.apsrtc.gov.in/Achievements.pdf |archivedate=21 February 2015 }}</ref>\n* Best Road Safety record for 2012\u201313<ref name=awards />\n\nAndhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation has a number of firsts to its credit in India.<ref name=\"apsrtc\" />\n* First to nationalize passenger Road Transport Services in the country - 1932\n* First to introduce long distance night express services\n* First to introduce A/C Sleeper, Hi-tech, Metro Liner, Inter-City Services and Metro Express\n* First to introduce depot computerisation - 1986\n* First to appoint Safety Commissioner for improving the safety of passengers\n* All 126 depots in the state are computerized\n* Reservation of tickets on telephone and door delivery of tickets\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Nizam State Railways - Road Transport Division|Nizam State Rail and Road Transport Department]].\n*\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://apsrtc.gov.in/ APSRTC official website]\n\n{{State agencies of Andhra Pradesh}}\n{{Road transport in Andhra Pradesh}}\n{{State owned road transport companies in India}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Transport companies established in 1932]]\n[[Category:Transport in Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:State agencies of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:State road transport corporations of India]]\n[[Category:1932 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian state bus operator}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Primary sources|1=article|date=March 2008}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Andhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation\n| logo                = Andhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation logo.png\n| industry            = [[Public transport bus service]]\n| type                = Public Sector Corporation under the Ministry of Transport of the State [[Government of Andhra Pradesh]]\n| products            = [[Bus transport]], courier and parcel service\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|1958|01|11}}\n| area_served         = [[Andhra Pradesh]]<br/>[[Chhattisgarh]]<br/>[[Karnataka]]<br/>[[Odisha]]<br/>[[Tamil Nadu]]<br/>[[Telangana]]<br/>[[Yanam]] ([[Puducherry]])\n| key_people          = {{Unbulleted list\n  | Perni Venkataramaiah {{Small|([[Ministry of Transport|Transport Minister]], [[Government of Andhra Pradesh|Govt. of Andhra Pradesh]])}}\n  | [[Surendra Babu|Nimmagadda Surendra Babu]] {{Small|([[Indian Police Service|I.P.S.]]) ([[Vice-Chairman]] and [[Managing director|MD]])}}\n  }}\n| revenue             = {{Increase}} {{INRConvert|51|b}}<ref name=\"news.outlookindia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://news.outlookindia.com/item.aspx?652096 |title=APSRTC Equals Indian Railways in Ferrying Passengers |work=Outlookindia.com |accessdate=2015-03-11 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| homepage            = {{URL|https://www.apsrtc.ap.gov.in/}}\n| hq_location_city    = [[Vijayawada|Vijayawada, Andhra Pradesh]]\n| hq_location_country = India\n}}\n\n'''Andhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation''' (abbreviated as '''APSRTC'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/ap-state-road-transport-corporation-merger-happening-sooner-than-expected/article27709442.ece|title=AP State Road Transport Corporation merger happening sooner than expected?|last=Varma|first=P. Sujatha|date=2019-06-10|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-06-10|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>) is the state-owned [[road transport]] corporation in the [[States and union territories of India|Indian state]] of [[Andhra Pradesh]]. Its headquarters is located at NTR Administrative Block of RTC House in [[Pandit Nehru bus station]] of [[Vijayawada]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Naidu to open RTC block today|url=http://www.thehansindia.com/posts/index/Andhra-Pradesh/2016-06-06/Naidu-to-open-RTC-block-today-/233065|accessdate=18 April 2017|work=The Hans India|language=en}}</ref> Many other Indian metro towns in [[Telangana]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Karnataka]], [[Odisha]], [[Yanam]] and [[Chhattisgarh]] are also linked with the APSRTC services.\n\nAPSRTC was the first state transport system which uses Live tracking facilities for tracking of busses. GPS (Global positioning system) is fixed in all types of busses.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correspondent|first=Our Special|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/naidu-launches-bus-tracking-system/article27560344.ece|title=Naidu launches bus-tracking system|date=2004-02-06|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAPSRTC was formed on 11 January 1958 as per ''Road Transport Corporations Act 1950''. Earlier, it was a part of [[Nizam State Railways - Road Transport Division|Nizam State Rail and Road Transport Department]].<ref name=\"apsrtc\">{{cite web|title=Profile |url=http://www.apsrtc.gov.in/profile.aspx |website=Andhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation |access-date=18 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315015215/http://apsrtc.gov.in/profile.aspx |archivedate=15 March 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\nConsequent upon [[Telangana movement|bifurcation of Andhra Pradesh state]] into Telangana and residual Andhra Pradesh, [[TSRTC]] is operated as a separate entity from 3 June 2015.[[APSRTC]] is working from Vijayawada (Pandit Nehru Bus Stand) as Headquarters for the state of  Andhra Pradesh.\n\n== Administration ==\nThe organisation is divided into four zones with twelve Regional Managers. It has a total of 11,678 buses (government-owned 8964; hire on rental 2714)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://apsrtc.gov.in/profile.aspx|title=APSRTC - Profile|website=apsrtc.gov.in|access-date=2018-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180930050308/http://www.apsrtc.gov.in/profile.aspx|archive-date=30 September 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> operating in {{Nowrap|44.15 lakh}} kilometers and has a total of 426 bus stations and 126 bus depots.<ref name=\"apsrtc\" /> From 30 January 2019, all the APSRTC vehicles in the state are registered as [[List of RTO districts in India|AP\u201339]], followed by \"Z\" and four digits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/vijayawada/2019/jan/31/new-ap-39-code-to-register-vehicles-in-state-launched-1932417.html|title=New \u2018AP 39\u2019 code to register vehicles in Andhra Pradesh launched|date=31 January 2019|work=The New Indian Express|accessdate=9 June 2019|location=Vijayawada}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\n[[File:Sattupalle - Eluru APS RTC bus on Polavaram canal.jpg|thumb|An APSRTC bus Enroute to [[Eluru]]]]\nAPSRTC operates various services, such as Vennela, Night Rider,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/visakhapatnam/apsrtc-adds-2-night-rider-buses-to-fleet/articleshow/68568807.cms|title=APSRTC adds 2 Night Rider buses to fleet|last=V|first=Kamalakara Rao|date=26 March 2019|website=The Times of India|location=Visakhapatnam|language=en|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref> Amaravati, Garuda Plus, Indra, Super Luxury, Ultra Deluxe / Deluxe, Express, Saptagiri Luxury, Saptagiri Express, Metro Express, Metro Luxury, Metro Luxury Semi Low Floor, Metro Deluxe, Telugu Velugu, City Ordinary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apsrtc.gov.in/Types%20Of%20Coaches.aspx|title=Types of Coaches of A.P.S.R.T.C.|website=A.P.S.R.T.C.|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Performance and earnings ==\n{{As of|February 2016}}, the organisation has a gross earnings of {{INRconvert|30.50|abbr=on}} per km., with a loss of {{INRconvert|-465000.8|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"apsrtc\" />\n\n== Awards and achievements ==\n* It entered the ''[[Guinness Book of World Records]]'' on 31 October 1999, with 22,000 buses making it the largest bus fleet in the world.<ref>{{cite news|title=RTC heads for split amid fears, anxiety|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Vijayawada/rtc-heads-for-split-amid-fears-anxiety/article6651459.ece|accessdate=18 March 2015|work=The Hindu|date=1 December 2014|location=Vijayawada}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Largest Fleet of Buses|url=http://www.worldrecordholdersclub.com/?p=592|work=worldrecordholdersclub|date=1 December 2012}}</ref>\n* Highest [[KMPL]] fuel efficiency for 2011-12 \u2013 Mofussil services and Vijayawada (urban division)<ref name=awards>{{cite web|title=APSRTC awards and achievements |url=http://www.apsrtc.gov.in/Achievements.pdf |publisher=Andhra_Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation |accessdate=18 March 2015 |format=PDF |date=7 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221115509/http://www.apsrtc.gov.in/Achievements.pdf |archivedate=21 February 2015 }}</ref>\n* Best Road Safety record for 2012\u201313<ref name=awards />\n\nAndhra Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation has a number of firsts to its credit in India.<ref name=\"apsrtc\" />\n* First to nationalize passenger Road Transport Services in the country - 1932\n* First to introduce long distance night express services\n* First to introduce A/C Sleeper, Hi-tech, Metro Liner, Inter-City Services and Metro Express\n* First to introduce depot computerisation - 1986\n* First to appoint Safety Commissioner for improving the safety of passengers\n* All 126 depots in the state are computerized\n* Reservation of tickets on telephone and door delivery of tickets\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Nizam State Railways - Road Transport Division|Nizam State Rail and Road Transport Department]].\n*\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://apsrtc.gov.in/ APSRTC official website]\n\n{{State agencies of Andhra Pradesh}}\n{{Road transport in Andhra Pradesh}}\n{{State owned road transport companies in India}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Transport companies established in 1932]]\n[[Category:Transport in Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:State agencies of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:State road transport corporations of India]]\n[[Category:1932 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Pavanipaul", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated the revenue.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andhra_Pradesh_State_Road_Transport_Corporation"}
{"title_page": "Richard Marggraf Turley", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Richard Marggraf Turley\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1970|8|2|df=yes}}\n| occupation  = Poet, literary critic}}\n\n'''Richard Marggraf Turley''' (born 2 August 1970) is a [[British people|British]] literary critic, poet and novelist. He specialises in Romanticism and the poetry of [[John Keats]], surveillance studies and ecocriticism. He is professor of English Literature at [[Aberystwyth University]], and between 2013 and 2018 was that institution's Professor of Engagement with the Public Imagination. \n\n==Life==\nMarggraf Turley was born in the [[Forest of Dean]]. He moved to Wales at the age of seven, was educated at [[King Henry VIII School, Abergavenny]], and read English at [[University of Leeds|Leeds University]].\n\n== Writer ==\nHe is author of three poetry collections: ''The Fossil Box'' (2007), concerned with the urgency of place and origins; ''Whiteout'' (2006), co-authored with Damian Walford Davies; and ''Wan-Hu's Flying Chair'' (2009), which won the 2010 [[Wales Book of the Year]] 'People's Choice' prize.\n\nIn 2007, he won first prize in the tenth-anniversary [[Keats-Shelley Prize for Poetry]]. His poem, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/donotmigrate/3668962/Elisions-by-Richard-Marggraf-Turley.html 'Elisions'], was written on the competition theme of slavery.\n\nIn 2010, together with Professor Reyer Zwiggelaar and Dr Bashar Rajoub of the Computer Science department at Aberystwyth University, Marggraf Turley conducted a 'Valentine's Day experiment' using thermal imaging cameras to determine whether reading love poetry produced distinct thermal signatures on the faces of volunteers.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2010/feb/13/valentines-love-poetry-hot-blood ''Guardian'' newspaper feature].</ref> \n\nIn March 2012, new research on Keats's ode 'To Autumn', co-authored with Dr Jayne Archer and Professor Howard Thomas (Aberystwyth University), was widely reported. Archival discoveries suggested that the 'stubble-plains' of Keats's ode '[[To Autumn]]' were located on St Giles's Hill, to the east of the City of Winchester, with implications for a new political reading of the poem. The part of St Giles's Hill in question now lies under a [[multi-storey car park]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/mar/23/john-keats-autumnal-idealist-social-commentator ''Guardian'' newspaper feature].</ref><ref>[http://blog.oup.com/2012/03/keats-ode-autumn-winchester-field/ Oxford University Press blog].</ref><ref>[http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/9613743.Keats__rural_idyll_now_a_car_park/ ''Southern Daily Echo''].</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2119109/Ode-NCP-How-cornfield-inspired-1819-poem-Keats-multi-storey-car-park.html ''Daily Mail'' newspaper feature].</ref> The editor of the Telegraph devoted 22 March 2012's editorial to an 'Ode to a Car Park'<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/telegraph-view/9160657/Ode-to-a-Car-Park.html ''Telegraph'' editorial].</ref>\n\nIn 2013, research by Marggraf Turley, Archer and Thomas on the importance of Shakespeare's business dealings as a grain merchant for such plays as [[King Lear]] and [[Coriolanus]] was widely reported.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-mid-wales-21993857|title=Shakespeare's past as food hoarder|date=2013-04-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-01-15|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bad-bard-a-tax-dodger-and-famine-profiteer-69qc5hrf2m3|title=Bad Bard: a tax dodger and famine profiteer|last=Leake|first=Jonathan|date=2013-03-31|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-01-15|issn=0956-1382}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2301829/Was-Shakespeare-tax-dodger-Bard-ruthless-businessman-exploited-famine-faced-jail-cheating-revenue.html|title=Was Shakespeare a tax dodger? Bard was 'ruthless businessman who exploited famine and faced jail for cheating revenue'|work=Mail Online|access-date=2018-01-15}}</ref> Their work also threw light on the significance of crop weeds such as darnel in King Lear.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/food-blog/wales-food-security-shakespeare-keats-fiction|title=Can Shakespeare and Keats address today's food security challenges?|last=Balch|first=Oliver|date=2014-05-01|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-01-15}}</ref>\n\nMarggraf Turley has written a number of books on and the [[Romantic poets]], including ''The Politics of Language in Romantic Literature'' (2002), ''Keats's Boyish Imagination'' (2004), ''Bright Stars: John Keats, Barry Cornwall and Romantic Literary Culture'' (2009), and \u2013 co-authored with Archer and Thomas \u2013 ''Food and the Literary Imagination'' (2015).\n\nHe is also author of a historical crime novel set in Romantic London of 1810, ''The Cunning House'' (2015).\n\nHe writes a blog on topics related to Romantic literature. In 2013, he was one of the three English-panel judges for the [[Wales Book of the Year]].\n\n== Poetry collections ==\n* 2009: ''Wan-Hu's Flying Chair'', Salt Press, {{ISBN|978-1844714438}}*\n* 2007: ''The Fossil-Box'', Cinnamon Press, {{ISBN|978-1-905614-35-6}} *\n* 2006: ''Whiteout'', co-authored with Damian Walford Davies, Parthian, {{ISBN|978-1-905762-15-6}}\n\n== Novel ==\n* 2015: ''The Cunning House'', Sandstone, {{ISBN|9781910124109}}\n\n== Critical studies ==\n* 2018: (ed.) ''Keats's Places'', Palgrave, {{ISBN|978-3319922423}}\n* 2015: (co-authored, Jayne Archer and Howard Thomas) ''Food and the Literary Imagination'', Palgrave, {{ISBN|978-1-137-40637-8}}\n* 2015: ''Writing Essays: A Guide for Students in English and the Humanities'', 2nd edn, Routledge, {{ISBN|978-1138916692}} \n* 2011: (ed.) ''The Writer in the Academy: Creative Interfrictions'', Boydell and Brewer, {{ISBN|978-1-84384-278-1}} \n* 2009: ''Bright Stars: Keats, Barry Cornwall and Romantic Literary Culture'', Liverpool University Press, {{ISBN|978-1-84631-211-3}} \n* 2006: (co-ed., Damian Walford Davies) ''The Monstrous Debt: Modalities of Romantic Influence in Twentieth-Century Literature'', Wayne State University Press, {{ISBN|978-0-8143-3058-6}} \n* 2004: ''Keats's Boyish Imagination'', Routledge, {{ISBN|978-0-415-28882-8}}  \n* 2002: ''The Politics of Language in Romantic Literature'', Palgrave Macmillan, {{ISBN|978-0-333-96898-7}}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n* 2007: [[Keats-Shelley Prize for Poetry]]\n* 2010: [[Wales Book of the Year]] \"People's Choice\" award (sponsored by [[Media Wales]])\n* 2015: ASLE/Inspire-UKI Prize Essay (with Jayne Archer and Howard Thomas)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/donotmigrate/3668962/Elisions-by-Richard-Marggraf-Turley.html Richard Marggraf Turley's poem, \"Elisions], ''The Telegraph'' \n* [https://www.aber.ac.uk/en/english/staff-profiles/listing/profile/rcm University profile ]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marggraf Turley, Richard}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British poets]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Academics of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:British literary critics]]\n[[Category:British male poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Richard Marggraf Turley\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1970|8|2|df=yes}}\n| occupation  = Poet, literary critic}}\n\n'''Richard Marggraf Turley''' (born 2 August 1970) is a [[British people|British]] literary critic, poet and novelist. He specialises in Romanticism and the poetry of [[John Keats]], surveillance studies and ecocriticism. He is professor of English Literature at [[Aberystwyth University]], and is that institution's Professor of Engagement with the Public Imagination. \n\n==Life==\nMarggraf Turley was born in the [[Forest of Dean]]. He moved to Wales at the age of seven, was educated at [[King Henry VIII School, Abergavenny]], and read English at [[University of Leeds|Leeds University]].\n\n== Writer ==\nHe is author of three poetry collections: ''The Fossil Box'' (2007), concerned with the urgency of place and origins; ''Whiteout'' (2006), co-authored with Damian Walford Davies; and ''Wan-Hu's Flying Chair'' (2009), which won the 2010 [[Wales Book of the Year]] 'People's Choice' prize.\n\nIn 2007, he won first prize in the tenth-anniversary [[Keats-Shelley Prize for Poetry]]. His poem, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/donotmigrate/3668962/Elisions-by-Richard-Marggraf-Turley.html 'Elisions'], was written on the competition theme of slavery.\n\nIn 2010, together with Professor Reyer Zwiggelaar and Dr Bashar Rajoub of the Computer Science department at Aberystwyth University, Marggraf Turley conducted a 'Valentine's Day experiment' using thermal imaging cameras to determine whether reading love poetry produced distinct thermal signatures on the faces of volunteers.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2010/feb/13/valentines-love-poetry-hot-blood ''Guardian'' newspaper feature].</ref> \n\nIn March 2012, new research on Keats's ode 'To Autumn', co-authored with Dr Jayne Archer and Professor Howard Thomas (Aberystwyth University), was widely reported. Archival discoveries suggested that the 'stubble-plains' of Keats's ode '[[To Autumn]]' were located on St Giles's Hill, to the east of the City of Winchester, with implications for a new political reading of the poem. The part of St Giles's Hill in question now lies under a [[multi-storey car park]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/mar/23/john-keats-autumnal-idealist-social-commentator ''Guardian'' newspaper feature].</ref><ref>[http://blog.oup.com/2012/03/keats-ode-autumn-winchester-field/ Oxford University Press blog].</ref><ref>[http://www.dailyecho.co.uk/news/9613743.Keats__rural_idyll_now_a_car_park/ ''Southern Daily Echo''].</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2119109/Ode-NCP-How-cornfield-inspired-1819-poem-Keats-multi-storey-car-park.html ''Daily Mail'' newspaper feature].</ref> The editor of the Telegraph devoted 22 March 2012's editorial to an 'Ode to a Car Park'<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/telegraph-view/9160657/Ode-to-a-Car-Park.html ''Telegraph'' editorial].</ref>\n\nIn 2013, research by Marggraf Turley, Archer and Thomas on the importance of Shakespeare's business dealings as a grain merchant for such plays as [[King Lear]] and [[Coriolanus]] was widely reported.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-mid-wales-21993857|title=Shakespeare's past as food hoarder|date=2013-04-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-01-15|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bad-bard-a-tax-dodger-and-famine-profiteer-69qc5hrf2m3|title=Bad Bard: a tax dodger and famine profiteer|last=Leake|first=Jonathan|date=2013-03-31|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-01-15|issn=0956-1382}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2301829/Was-Shakespeare-tax-dodger-Bard-ruthless-businessman-exploited-famine-faced-jail-cheating-revenue.html|title=Was Shakespeare a tax dodger? Bard was 'ruthless businessman who exploited famine and faced jail for cheating revenue'|work=Mail Online|access-date=2018-01-15}}</ref> Their work also threw light on the significance of crop weeds such as darnel in King Lear.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/food-blog/wales-food-security-shakespeare-keats-fiction|title=Can Shakespeare and Keats address today's food security challenges?|last=Balch|first=Oliver|date=2014-05-01|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-01-15}}</ref>\n\nMarggraf Turley has written a number of books on and the [[Romantic poets]], including ''The Politics of Language in Romantic Literature'' (2002), ''Keats's Boyish Imagination'' (2004), ''Bright Stars: John Keats, Barry Cornwall and Romantic Literary Culture'' (2009), and \u2013 co-authored with Archer and Thomas \u2013 ''Food and the Literary Imagination'' (2015).\n\nHe is also author of a historical crime novel set in Romantic London of 1810, ''The Cunning House'' (2015).\n\nHe writes a blog on topics related to Romantic literature. In 2013, he was one of the three English-panel judges for the [[Wales Book of the Year]].\n\n== Poetry collections ==\n* 2009: ''Wan-Hu's Flying Chair'', Salt Press, {{ISBN|978-1844714438}}*\n* 2007: ''The Fossil-Box'', Cinnamon Press, {{ISBN|978-1-905614-35-6}} *\n* 2006: ''Whiteout'', co-authored with Damian Walford Davies, Parthian, {{ISBN|978-1-905762-15-6}}\n\n== Novel ==\n* 2015: ''The Cunning House'', Sandstone, {{ISBN|9781910124109}}\n\n== Critical studies ==\n* 2018: (ed.) ''Keats's Places'', Palgrave, {{ISBN|978-3319922423}}\n* 2015: (co-authored, Jayne Archer and Howard Thomas) ''Food and the Literary Imagination'', Palgrave, {{ISBN|978-1-137-40637-8}}\n* 2015: ''Writing Essays: A Guide for Students in English and the Humanities'', 2nd edn, Routledge, {{ISBN|978-1138916692}} \n* 2011: (ed.) ''The Writer in the Academy: Creative Interfrictions'', Boydell and Brewer, {{ISBN|978-1-84384-278-1}} \n* 2009: ''Bright Stars: Keats, Barry Cornwall and Romantic Literary Culture'', Liverpool University Press, {{ISBN|978-1-84631-211-3}} \n* 2006: (co-ed., Damian Walford Davies) ''The Monstrous Debt: Modalities of Romantic Influence in Twentieth-Century Literature'', Wayne State University Press, {{ISBN|978-0-8143-3058-6}} \n* 2004: ''Keats's Boyish Imagination'', Routledge, {{ISBN|978-0-415-28882-8}}  \n* 2002: ''The Politics of Language in Romantic Literature'', Palgrave Macmillan, {{ISBN|978-0-333-96898-7}}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n* 2007: [[Keats-Shelley Prize for Poetry]]\n* 2010: [[Wales Book of the Year]] \"People's Choice\" award (sponsored by [[Media Wales]])\n* 2015: ASLE/Inspire-UKI Prize Essay (with Jayne Archer and Howard Thomas)\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/donotmigrate/3668962/Elisions-by-Richard-Marggraf-Turley.html Richard Marggraf Turley's poem, \"Elisions], ''The Telegraph'' \n* [https://www.aber.ac.uk/en/english/staff-profiles/listing/profile/rcm University profile ]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marggraf Turley, Richard}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British poets]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Welsh poets]]\n[[Category:Academics of Aberystwyth University]]\n[[Category:British literary critics]]\n[[Category:British male poets]]\n", "name_user": "Loveableshovable", "label": "safe", "comment": "edited to reflect change in Professor of Engagement with the Public Imagination status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Marggraf_Turley"}
